column1: oh well, at least the Sox still won.

column3: This year more than any other in&nbsp
column4: my lifetime, at least, we really need a Democrat in the White House, and I'm not just saying that 'cause I am one (at least, will be when i freakin' turn 18).&nbsp
column5: This country is headed in the wrong direction on so many levels.&nbsp
column6: Our economy is a huge issue.&nbsp
column7: That's a given.&nbsp
column8: I mean, just look at what's happened since President Bush sent forces to Iraq.&nbsp
column9: I know 9/11 was a huge factor in the recession, but the war kept us from recovering.&nbsp
column10: It's like pouring acid onto a healing scab, if that's not too gross.&nbsp
column11: We basically all know what's happened there.&nbsp
column12: I mean, all you have to do is drive and shop to know.&nbsp

column1: Bigger than anything else is the fact that our own people are out there, dying for a cause that can't be resolved with warfare.
column2: Don't our leaders realize that we are dealing with a new kind of kamikaze fighters, people who are willing to kill themselves as well as their own kind to secure their troubled fight?&nbsp
column3: Invading the Middle East is not going to stop them, but instead give them yet another reason to hurt us.&nbsp
column4: They'll fight till they die, or we do, whichever comes first.&nbsp
column5: We need to stop it all now before we've gone any farther.&nbsp
column6: I mean, even I'm getting to the age where I'll start seeing my own friends drafted overseas.&nbsp
column7: (That is, if even more soldiers are needed in the years to come).&nbsp
column8: Bush got us into this mess.&nbsp
column9: I'm sorry, but I just don't trust him to pull us out of it.&nbsp
column10: Plus, his ""military experience,"" if you can call it that, isn't even.&nbsp
column11: Kerry is a Vietnam vet
column12: he knows what an illegitimate war is about.&nbsp
column13: We need someone with that kind of knowledge to stop the insanity.

column1: 'Kay, those are just two reasons why I think our country is headed in the wrong direction.
column2: Then of course, there are so many other reasons.&nbsp
column4: Haha, I've probably offended enough people already.&nbsp
column5: I hope I haven't!! :(&nbsp
column6: It's just politics.&nbsp
column7: Everyone is different, everyone has their own opinion.&nbsp
column8: This just happens to be mine.&nbsp

column3:
And vote, if you're old enough, no matter who you're voting for!! :)

Dad: ""Now, can you IM people on a laptop?""

column1: on the way home from Maine we were hit with a downfall of torrential rains... seriously, i've never seen anything that bad.
column2: it got so bad that we couldn't see the taillights of the car right very in front of us.&nbsp
column3: my mom, ever so nervous, made us pull into a rest stop in Kennebunkport
column4: incidentaly, the very same one we stopped at on our way up to our first trip to Maine, which got me even more melancholy - where the rain only got worse.
column5: The place lost power, and their manager was running around acting all worried, and talking to some other road stop manager over a cell phone.&nbsp
column6: He mentioned the in-effect tornado warning for that very county just a liiiiitle too loudly.&nbsp
column7: Weyellll, I of course began to freak out.&nbsp
column8: The fact that I was already a moody, pmsing, emotional mess didn't help matters much, either.&nbsp
column9: plus dad was still out in the car, since he didn't wanna run in through the rain and get all wet.&nbsp
column10: ugh.&nbsp
column11: Mom, after hearing about the funnel cloud directly above us, actually hesitated in getting dad.&nbsp
column12: he probably didn't know about it, and i know i wouldn't wanna be outside during a tornado, but she <U>still</U> wouldn't let either me or julie go.&nbsp
column13: (she didn't want us to get wet).&nbsp
column14: Sooo she took her time in looking for a plastic bag to put over her head, and when she didn't find one, she went into the little gift shop to peruse through the t-shirt rack to protect her from the water.&nbsp
column15: well by that time i was getting pretty annoyed, and just decided to go out without telling her, but at the doors&nbsp
column17: (on a side note, if the person I loved was in even slight danger of a tornado or anything, a little bit of water wouldn't keep me from them in an instant.&nbsp
column19: Well needless to say there was no tornado, but I'm still a little dazed by the whole affair.&nbsp
column20: Never thought I'd have to deal with another tornado warning, let alone in Maine of all places.&nbsp

column1: yeah, i'm just a liiiiitle grouchy today.

column2: Today I went to the Adams houses, in Quincy, fiiiinally!!&nbsp
column4: Don't laugh at me, it really was.&nbsp
column5: Dude, he's like.. my idol.
column6: Okay, you can ex-out now if you want, but I'm dead serious!!&nbsp
column7: I was in the house where he was born, stood on the same floorboards as he once stood on, looked at the fireplace where, for ten years, Abigail wrote all her letters to her far-off husband.. okay, I know, I sound pretty ridonculous now.&nbsp
column8: But it really was awesome.&nbsp
column9: There were three houses in all.&nbsp
column10: The first two were pretty small and all warped.. sheesh, y'all know how short I am and the doorframes were only a few inches over my head.&nbsp
column11: People were short, back in the day.&nbsp
column12: Anyways, the third house was much bigger, since they lived there after they lived in Paris and were like, richer and stuff.&nbsp
column13: It had all their furniture.. including the chair where he died.
column14: He died on the 50th anniversary of the Fourth of July, and his last words were ""Jefferson lives.""&nbsp
column15: But, Jefferson, who was nine years younger, had also died on that fiftieth anniversary day.. only four hours earlier.&nbsp

column1: okay, well, you all are probably rolling your eyes in shame at me so I'm gonna stop all this for now.

column3: I'm gonna write a LOT today.&nbsp
column4: I just got home from a week in Maine at my cousins' house, in Caribou.&nbsp
column5: If you don't know where that is, just look at the highest tip of the state on a map, and there you go.&nbsp
column6: They had this awesome cabin on a lake, and they had a boat and waterskiing and really good lobster... aaah okay, I need to breathe for a second.&nbsp
column7: Breaathe.&nbsp
column8: Brreeeeaaathe.&nbsp
column9: &nbsp
column10: OK.

column1: We left on Saturday morning, the four of us, in the good ol' aqua blue minivan packed tight with.. so much stuff.
column3: We went north through Boston, across the North Shore, and through New Hampshire for like ten minutes (okay maybe a little longer than that) before we hit Maine.&nbsp
column4: Gosh, those New Hampshioners sure are rude!&nbsp
column5: You're in their state for a split second when you're trying to get from Massachusetts to Maine, and they hit you with a toll that usually is backed up at least a mile or so.&nbsp
column6: Pfft.&nbsp
column7: Anywhom we finally got through the damn tollbooths and Maine wasn't very far off.&nbsp
column8: Surprise surprise, I'd never been in that state before.&nbsp
column9: But yey, I crossed the border, and was in!&nbsp
column10: We drove and drove some more.&nbsp
column11: I listened to every BNL song on the planet at least eight times each.&nbsp
column12: Finally we stopped for the night in Bangor, a city about halfway up.&nbsp
column13: And wow, Maine is really huge!&nbsp
column14: I never even realized.&nbsp
column15: They say that one of their counties, Aristook County, the one I was staying in, was larger than Massachusetts.&nbsp
column17: Yeah, it's one cool state, and I'm not even being sarcastic!

column1: One silly little side note is that my uncle Jay and aunt Cathy, who live right here in Bridgewater on Fox Hill Drive, were still in Boston when we were in Kennebunkport, ME at a rest stop eating lunch.
column2: Kennebunkport isn't too far from Bangor.&nbsp
column3: It is also the summer residence of Daddy Bush and the W.&nbsp
column4: But anyways, we thought we were so smart and cool for a while because ohhh, Jay expected that we'd back out of the whole trip before we even left and his family are the travel people anyways.&nbsp
column5: Swear to God, they could go to Connecticut for a loaf of bread and not even think twice on it.&nbsp
column6: Soooo, when they strangely arrived in Bangor ten minutes after we did... well, whatever.&nbsp
column7: It's all my dad's fault, he drives 55 on the highways.

column2: So we left the next day after driving around Bangor looking for a church for at least an hour and subsequently giving up, and before long we were in the middle of rural Maine, the middle of nowhere.&nbsp
column3: We stopped to use the bathroom sometime that day, getting off at an exit that advertised a nearby Citgo station.&nbsp
column4: Well, that Citgo was about twenty miles down the road from the exit, and what it really was was this little diner with a gas pump outside.&nbsp
column5: A bunch of old people were sitting around inside, and you could tell that they all knew each others' names and business and stuff.&nbsp
column6: It was really very cool.&nbsp
column7: OK, we got back on the high way till, finally, we hit Caribou!&nbsp
column8: (OH yeah, right next to Caribou was, incidentaly, Bridgewater ME.&nbsp
column9: Go figure).&nbsp

column1: We waited around for Jay, who arrived, once again, twenty minutes after us even though we'd left Bangor an hour earlier.
column3: We had a rendez-vous at the local Shop n' Save, and proceded to my cousins' house for dinner.&nbsp
column4: I met my cousins there for the first time, and they are all so awesome!&nbsp
column5: Really outgoing, which was a huge relief.&nbsp
column6: I was scared they'd be all teenager-y and quiet, but that wasn't the case at all.&nbsp
column7: The five of us ate dinner at our own little table, and went downstairs to watch their tapes of them waterskiing.&nbsp
column8: They were in the process of trying to convince Julie and me to do it.&nbsp
column9: My mom was, at the time, adamantly against it.&nbsp
column10: Justin, who's my age, tried to convince her while the rest of us were still watching, but she was all Mom-ish and I guess she gave him one of her evil teacher glares.&nbsp
column11: Anyways, he didn't ask her about it anymore!&nbsp
column14: Jordan, who was my sisters' age, kind of made us shoot his gun-thing at a target in the basement.&nbsp
column16: I'd never held a gun before so much as shot one, so that was.. interesting.&nbsp

column1: Weyell, we finally went to their camp house after dinner, which turned out to be beautiful.
column2: Right on the lake, with no cars or airplanes or trains buzzing around us like in Bridgewater.. it was awesome.&nbsp
column3: I won't get into everything that happened the whole week, sheesh this is already long enough, but still... That night we went out on their boat, while my cousins did their whole waterskiing act.&nbsp
column5: During my one feeble attempt, I couldn't even get up.&nbsp
column6: Julie did better than me, ha ha.&nbsp
column7: Oh well.

column1: Over the next few days, I saw the auroras for the first time, saw my first moose, re-learned how to play Cribbage, drove
column4: haha), went water-tubing, saw a million ducks, heard loons, had a campfire, made s'mores, fell in love with their dog Madison (who actually tapped you with his paw if you stopped petting him.&nbsp
column5: adorable.)&nbsp
column6: , took a day trip and explored rural Canada (lol, i know), ate lobster, had my first scarlet red Maine hotdog, went a week without my computer or television and didn't miss it at alllll, slept in my first dormitory (sort of), and had so much fun.&nbsp
column7: whew.&nbsp
column8: okay.

column2: i'm really very sorry about that.&nbsp

column1: My mom and I were in the kitchen making dinner when her cellphone rang.
column2: That was pretty odd since the only people who ever call her, albeit the only ones who even know her number, are me, Julie, and Dad.&nbsp
column3: Julie was watching TV and Dad was in the family room.&nbsp
column4: I answered it for her, and to my great surprise this Spanish guy was screaming on the other end, demanding that some Elaine pick up and talk to him.&nbsp
column5: ""Elaine!&nbsp
column6: Elaine!&nbsp
column7: *unrecognizable spanish screaming*
column8: ELAINE!""&nbsp
column9: He sounded like he was in a car.&nbsp
column10: I handed my mom the phone and could still hear him from across the room.&nbsp
column11: She said, in her teachery no-nonsense-from-me-you-chauvinistic-bastard tone of voice ""there is no Elaine here, for the third time, go away, goodbye!""&nbsp
column12: She hung up the phone, the guy screaming in Spanish all the while.&nbsp
column14: Apparently the guy had called her before, but she thought it was no big deal and didn't tell anybody.&nbsp
column16: We called Verizon and had her number changed.. probably the same thing the original Elaine had done.&nbsp

column1: I mean, my mom's had her phone for a few weeks now, which means that this Elaine
column2: must have discontinued that number a&nbsp
column5: If this Elaine had wanted the man to keep in touch with her, she surely would have given him her new number by now.&nbsp
column6: Maybe, just maybe, she changed the number just to get away from this guy.&nbsp
column7: I mean, I would have too!&nbsp
column8: People don't usually scare me but talking to this guy for those .2 seconds did.&nbsp
column9: I'm a little creeped out by this whole thing.&nbsp
column10: Hah, I'm the only one too.&nbsp
column11: As usual!

column5: &nbsp
